        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The Mitchell Loeb Papers consists of 223 items total, covering a number of different mediums. It includes 35 posters, 141 drawings, seven graphic items, nine pamphlets, 23 black and white photographs, three 8x10 negatives and five newspaper clippings. Dated items range from the mid 1930s to the mid 1950s and consist mainly of work done by Loeb himself for the ILGWU and the Jewish Daily Forward.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <relatedmaterial id="ref4">
            <head>Related Archival Materials</head>
            <p>Works produced by Mitchell Loeb can also be founded in the Eugene V. Debs Papers (TAM 020) and ILGWU Paintings, Photographs, and Memorabilia held by the Kheel Center for Labor-Management Documentation and Archives at Cornell University.</p>
        </relatedmaterial>
        <bioghist id="ref11">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Mitchell Loeb (1889-1968) was an artist and cartoonist whose work reflected his support for labor, liberal Democrats, and Jewish Palestine. Loeb was born in Poland and came to the United States as a teenager. For a short period after World War I, Loeb was an artist for 
                <emph render="italic">The Jewish Daily Forward</emph> and 
                <emph render="italic">The Jewish Day</emph>. After, he ran a commercial art studio in New York City.</p>
        </bioghist>
